1
00:00:33,366 --> 00:00:35,994
He was the phenomenon
of the twenties.

2
00:00:36,036 --> 00:00:40,302
When you think that he was
as well-known as Lindbergh...

3
00:00:40,340 --> 00:00:42,535
it's really quite astonishing.

4
00:00:45,245 --> 00:00:48,874
His story reflected the nature
of our civilization...

5
00:00:48,915 --> 00:00:50,883
the character of our times.

6
00:00:50,917 --> 00:00:53,943
Yet it was also
one man's story...

7
00:00:53,987 --> 00:00:57,445
and all the themes
of our culture were there...

8
00:00:57,490 --> 00:01:00,323
heroism, will,
things like that...

9
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:04,228
but when you look back on it,
it was very strange.

10
00:01:05,865 --> 00:01:07,958
Well, it is ironic...

11
00:01:08,001 --> 00:01:11,129
to see how quickly
he has faded from memory...

12
00:01:11,171 --> 00:01:14,470
considering what
an astounding record he made.

13
00:01:14,507 --> 00:01:16,975
He was,
of course, very amusing...

14
00:01:17,010 --> 00:01:20,969
but at the same time
touched a nerve in people...

15
00:01:21,014 --> 00:01:26,475
perhaps in a way in which they
would prefer not to be touched.

16
00:01:26,519 --> 00:01:29,920
It certainly is
a very bizarre story.

17
00:01:44,237 --> 00:01:46,797
The year is 1928.

18
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:50,799
America, enjoying a decade
of unequaled prosperity...

19
00:01:50,844 --> 00:01:52,402
has gone wild.

20
00:01:52,445 --> 00:01:54,572
The Jazz Age, it is called.

21
00:01:54,614 --> 00:01:58,277
The rhythms are syncopated.
The morals are looser.

22
00:01:58,318 --> 00:02:00,946
The liquor is cheaper,
when you can get it.

23
00:02:00,987 --> 00:02:06,425
It is a time of diverse heroes
and madcap stunts...

24
00:02:06,459 --> 00:02:10,259
of speak-easies
and flamboyant parties.

25
00:02:10,296 --> 00:02:13,094
One typical party occurs
at the Long Island estate...

26
00:02:13,133 --> 00:02:16,466
of Mr. And Mrs.
Henry Porter Sutton...

27
00:02:16,503 --> 00:02:19,563
socialites,
patrons of the arts.

28
00:02:19,606 --> 00:02:21,073
Politicians and poets...

29
00:02:21,107 --> 00:02:24,076
rub elbows
with the cream of high society.

30
00:02:24,110 --> 00:02:27,079
Present at the party
is Scott Fitzgerald...

31
00:02:27,113 --> 00:02:29,445
who is to cast perspective
on the twenties...

32
00:02:29,482 --> 00:02:31,780
for all future generations.

33
00:02:31,818 --> 00:02:33,149
He writes in his notebook...

34
00:02:33,186 --> 00:02:36,155
about a curious little man
named Leon Selwyn, or Zelman...

35
00:02:36,189 --> 00:02:39,158
who seemed clearly
to be an aristocrat...

36
00:02:39,192 --> 00:02:43,720
and extolled the very rich
as he chatted with socialites.

37
00:02:43,763 --> 00:02:46,732
He spoke adoringly of Coolidge
and the Republican Party...

38
00:02:46,766 --> 00:02:49,564
all in an upper-class
Boston accent.

39
00:02:49,602 --> 00:02:51,467
"An hour later,"
writes Fitzgerald...

40
00:02:51,504 --> 00:02:54,473
"I was stunned
to see the same man...

41
00:02:54,507 --> 00:02:56,475
"speaking with
the kitchen help.

42
00:02:56,509 --> 00:02:59,307
"Now he claimed
to be a Democrat...

43
00:02:59,345 --> 00:03:04,248
"and his accent seemed coarse,
as if he were one of the crowd."

44
00:03:04,284 --> 00:03:07,811
It's the first small notice
taken of Leonard Zelig.

45
00:03:07,854 --> 00:03:10,550
Florida, one year later.

46
00:03:10,590 --> 00:03:12,490
An odd incident occurs...

47
00:03:12,525 --> 00:03:15,494
at the New York Yankees'
training camp.

48
00:03:15,528 --> 00:03:17,428
Journalists,
anxious as always...

49
00:03:17,463 --> 00:03:21,627
to immortalize the exploits
of the great home-run hitters...

50
00:03:21,668 --> 00:03:23,636
notice a strange new player...

51
00:03:23,670 --> 00:03:26,639
waiting his turn at bat
after Babe Ruth.

52
00:03:26,673 --> 00:03:28,766
He's listed on the roster
as Lou Zelig...

53
00:03:28,808 --> 00:03:32,300
but no one on the team
has heard of him.

54
00:03:32,345 --> 00:03:33,437
Security guards are called...

55
00:03:33,479 --> 00:03:35,276
and he's escorted
from the premises.

56
00:03:35,315 --> 00:03:40,378
It appears as a small item
in the next day's newspaper.

57
00:03:47,360 --> 00:03:49,828
Chicago, Illinois,
that same year.

58
00:03:49,862 --> 00:03:51,955
There is a private party...

59
00:03:51,998 --> 00:03:54,831
at a speak-easy
on the South Side.

60
00:03:54,867 --> 00:03:57,062
People from the most
respectable walks of life...

61
00:03:57,103 --> 00:04:00,266
dance and drink bathtub gin.

62
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:09,371
Present that evening
was Calvin Turner, a waiter.

63
00:04:09,415 --> 00:04:12,384
A lot of gangsters
come in the place.

64
00:04:12,418 --> 00:04:15,387
They're good tippers
and take care of us.

65
00:04:15,421 --> 00:04:17,787
We take care of our customers.

66
00:04:17,824 --> 00:04:21,282
On this particular night,
here's a strange guy coming in.

67
00:04:21,327 --> 00:04:23,090
I'd never seen him before.

68
00:04:23,129 --> 00:04:24,255
So I asked the one
or the other...

69
00:04:24,297 --> 00:04:26,094
I said, "John,
you know this guy?

70
00:04:26,132 --> 00:04:27,690
"You ever seen him?"
So he looks.

71
00:04:27,734 --> 00:04:29,463
"No. I ain't never
seen him before.

72
00:04:29,502 --> 00:04:30,696
"I don't know who he is...

73
00:04:30,737 --> 00:04:32,432
"but I know one thing...
he's a tough-Iooking hombre."

74
00:04:32,472 --> 00:04:34,201
So I looked over, and then...

75
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:35,707
the next thing,
the guy had disappeared.

76
00:04:35,742 --> 00:04:38,040
I don't know where he went to.

77
00:04:38,077 --> 00:04:40,545
But about this time,
the music starts...

78
00:04:40,580 --> 00:04:42,707
and the band
started playing.

79
00:04:42,749 --> 00:04:46,708
I looked. Here's a colored boy
over there playing trumpet.

80
00:04:46,753 --> 00:04:50,382
Man, he was playing back,
and I looked at the guy...

81
00:04:50,423 --> 00:04:52,789
and I said, "He looks
just like that gangster...

82
00:04:52,825 --> 00:04:57,728
"but the gangster was white,
and this guy is black."

83
00:04:57,764 --> 00:05:00,790
So I don't know
what's happening.

84
00:05:00,867 --> 00:05:05,065
New York City.
It is several months later.

85
00:05:05,104 --> 00:05:09,040
Police are investigating
the disappearance of a clerk...

86
00:05:09,075 --> 00:05:10,542
named Leonard Zelig.

87
00:05:10,576 --> 00:05:12,874
Both his landlady
and his employer...

88
00:05:12,912 --> 00:05:14,709
have reported him missing.

89
00:05:14,747 --> 00:05:19,275
They tell police he was an odd
little man who kept to himself.

90
00:05:19,319 --> 00:05:22,379
Two clues are found in
Zelig's Greenwich Village flat.

91
00:05:22,422 --> 00:05:27,985
One, a photograph of Zelig
with Eugene O'Neill...

92
00:05:28,027 --> 00:05:31,292
and one of him as Pagliacci.

93
00:05:34,367 --> 00:05:39,236
Acting on a tip, they trace
his whereabouts to Chinatown...

94
00:05:39,272 --> 00:05:42,241
where, in the rear
of a Chinese establishment...

95
00:05:42,275 --> 00:05:44,300
a strange-Iooking Oriental...

96
00:05:44,344 --> 00:05:47,802
who fits the description
of Leonard Zelig is discovered.

97
00:05:47,847 --> 00:05:51,305
Suspicious, the detectives
try to pull off his disguise...

98
00:05:51,351 --> 00:05:55,788
but it is not a disguise,
and a fight breaks out.

99
00:05:55,822 --> 00:05:59,622
He is removed by force
and taken to Manhattan Hospital.

100
00:05:59,659 --> 00:06:02,719
In the ambulance,
he rants and curses...

101
00:06:02,762 --> 00:06:05,230
in what sounds
like authentic Chinese.

102
00:06:05,264 --> 00:06:08,631
He is restrained
with a straitjacket.

103
00:06:08,668 --> 00:06:12,126
When he emerges from the car
twenty minutes later...

104
00:06:12,171 --> 00:06:16,801
incredibly, he is no longer
Chinese, but Caucasian.

105
00:06:16,843 --> 00:06:19,812
Bewildered interns place him
in the emergency room...

106
00:06:19,846 --> 00:06:21,814
for observation.

107
00:06:21,848 --> 00:06:25,545
At 7 a.m., Dr. Eudora Fletcher,
a psychiatrist...

108
00:06:25,585 --> 00:06:28,816
makes her usual rounds.

109
00:06:28,855 --> 00:06:31,824
When I first heard
about this emergency case...

110
00:06:31,858 --> 00:06:33,826
I didn't think
anything peculiar...

111
00:06:33,860 --> 00:06:36,829
and when I first
laid eyes on him...

112
00:06:36,863 --> 00:06:42,893
it was a bit strange because
I mistook him for a doctor.

113
00:06:42,935 --> 00:06:46,530
He had a very professional
demeanor about him.

114
00:06:46,572 --> 00:06:48,437
As a young psychiatrist...

115
00:06:48,474 --> 00:06:51,443
Eudora Fletcher is fascinated
by Leonard Zelig.

116
00:06:51,477 --> 00:06:54,776
She convinces the conservative
staff at the hospital...

117
00:06:54,814 --> 00:06:57,647
to allow her to pursue
a study of the new admission.

118
00:06:57,683 --> 00:07:00,083
So, what do you do?

119
00:07:00,119 --> 00:07:02,110
Oh, me? I'm a psychiatrist.

120
00:07:03,456 --> 00:07:07,187
I work mostly
with delusional paranoids.

121
00:07:07,226 --> 00:07:09,285
Tell me about it.

122
00:07:09,328 --> 00:07:10,795
There's not much to tell.

123
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:13,298
I work mostly
on the continent...

124
00:07:13,332 --> 00:07:16,301
and I've written quite a few
psychoanalytic papers.

125
00:07:16,335 --> 00:07:19,133
I worked with Freud in Vienna.

126
00:07:19,172 --> 00:07:21,970
We broke over the concept
of penis envy.

127
00:07:22,008 --> 00:07:26,035
Freud felt that it
should be limited to women.

128
00:07:26,078 --> 00:07:30,037
It's not that he was
making any sense at all.

129
00:07:30,082 --> 00:07:33,051
It was a conglomeration
of psychological double-talk...

130
00:07:33,085 --> 00:07:35,053
that he had apparently heard...

131
00:07:35,087 --> 00:07:37,351
or was familiar with
through reading.

132
00:07:37,390 --> 00:07:39,290
The funny thing was
his delivery was quite fluid...

133
00:07:39,325 --> 00:07:41,793
and might have been
convincing...

134
00:07:41,828 --> 00:07:45,025
to someone
who did not know any better.

135
00:07:45,064 --> 00:07:48,033
Who was this Leonard Zelig
that seemed to create...

136
00:07:48,067 --> 00:07:50,035
such diverse impressions
everywhere?

137
00:07:50,069 --> 00:07:54,062
All that was known of him
was that he was the son...

138
00:07:54,106 --> 00:07:57,075
of a Yiddish actor
named Morris Zelig...

139
00:07:57,109 --> 00:07:58,974
whose performance as Puck...

140
00:07:59,011 --> 00:08:02,412
in the Orthodox version of
"A Midsummer Night's Dream"...

141
00:08:02,448 --> 00:08:04,916
was coolly received.

142
00:08:04,951 --> 00:08:07,010
The elder Zelig's
second marriage...

143
00:08:07,053 --> 00:08:10,750
is marked by constant violent
quarreling, so much so...

144
00:08:10,790 --> 00:08:13,759
that although the family
lives over a bowling alley...

145
00:08:13,793 --> 00:08:16,990
it's the bowling alley
that complains of noise.

146
00:08:17,029 --> 00:08:21,591
As a boy, Leonard is frequently
bullied by anti-Semites.

147
00:08:21,634 --> 00:08:24,603
His parents,
who never take his part...

148
00:08:24,637 --> 00:08:28,630
and blame him for everything,
side with the anti-Semites.

149
00:08:28,674 --> 00:08:32,610
They punish him often
by locking him in a dark closet.

150
00:08:32,645 --> 00:08:34,613
When they are really angry...

151
00:08:34,647 --> 00:08:37,343
they get into the closet
with him.

152
00:08:37,383 --> 00:08:40,352
On his deathbed,
Morris Zelig tells his son...

153
00:08:40,386 --> 00:08:43,355
that life is a meaningless
nightmare of suffering...

154
00:08:43,389 --> 00:08:48,486
and the only advice he gives him
is to save string.

155
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:51,292
Though brother Jack
has a nervous breakdown...

156
00:08:51,330 --> 00:08:54,663
and sister Ruth becomes
a shoplifter and alcoholic...

157
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:58,136
Leonard Zelig appears
to have adjusted to life.

158
00:08:58,170 --> 00:09:01,071
Somehow, he seems to have coped.

159
00:09:01,107 --> 00:09:06,602
And then, suddenly,
increasingly strange behavior.

160
00:09:08,381 --> 00:09:11,145
Fascinated
by the Zelig phenomenon...

161
00:09:11,183 --> 00:09:14,152
Dr. Fletcher arranges
a series of experiments...

162
00:09:14,186 --> 00:09:17,713
and invites the skeptical staff
to observe.

163
00:09:17,757 --> 00:09:23,593
With the doctors watching, Zelig
becomes a perfect psychiatrist.

164
00:09:23,629 --> 00:09:27,087
When two Frenchmen
are brought in...

165
00:09:27,133 --> 00:09:31,035
Zelig assumes their characters
and speaks reasonable French.

166
00:09:31,070 --> 00:09:34,039
In the company
of a Chinese person...

167
00:09:34,073 --> 00:09:37,304
he begins to develop
Oriental features.

168
00:09:37,343 --> 00:09:40,801
By now, word has gotten out
to the press...

169
00:09:40,846 --> 00:09:43,815
and the public, thirsting
for thrills and novelty...

170
00:09:43,849 --> 00:09:46,147
is immediately captivated.

171
00:09:49,155 --> 00:09:51,487
The clamor is so great...

172
00:09:51,524 --> 00:09:55,426
that Dr. Allan Sindell
is forced to issue a statement.

173
00:09:55,461 --> 00:09:57,952
We're beginning
to realize the dimensions...

174
00:09:57,997 --> 00:10:01,125
of what could be the scientific
medical phenomenon of the age...

175
00:10:01,167 --> 00:10:03,567
and possibly of all time.

176
00:10:03,603 --> 00:10:05,935
Fresh stories roll off
the press every day...

177
00:10:05,972 --> 00:10:08,998
about Zelig
and his puzzling condition.

178
00:10:09,041 --> 00:10:13,000
Although the doctors claim
to have the situation in hand...

179
00:10:13,045 --> 00:10:16,446
no two can agree
on a diagnosis.

180
00:10:16,482 --> 00:10:18,973
I'm convinced
it's glandular in nature...

181
00:10:19,018 --> 00:10:21,486
and although there's
no evidence of misfunction...

182
00:10:21,520 --> 00:10:24,921
further tests will show
a problem in the secretions.

183
00:10:24,957 --> 00:10:28,222
It's something he picked up
from eating Mexican food.

184
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:30,728
This manifestation
is neurological in origin.

185
00:10:30,763 --> 00:10:34,221
This patient is suffering
from a brain tumor...

186
00:10:34,266 --> 00:10:39,169
and I should not be surprised
if within several weeks he died.

187
00:10:39,205 --> 00:10:43,164
We have not been able
to locate the tumor...

188
00:10:43,209 --> 00:10:45,074
but we're still looking.

189
00:10:45,111 --> 00:10:48,672
Ironically,
within two weeks' time...

190
00:10:48,714 --> 00:10:52,673
it is Dr. Birsky himself
who dies of a brain tumor.

191
00:10:52,718 --> 00:10:55,482
Leonard Zelig is fine.

192
00:10:55,621 --> 00:10:58,681
Throughout the weeks
of testing and speculation...

193
00:10:58,724 --> 00:11:00,624
Eudora Fletcher
begins to feel...

194
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:03,128
that the patient
might be suffering...

195
00:11:03,162 --> 00:11:05,130
not from
a physiological disorder...

196
00:11:05,164 --> 00:11:07,632
but from a psychological one.

197
00:11:07,667 --> 00:11:11,125
It is Zelig's unstable makeup,
she suggests...

198
00:11:11,170 --> 00:11:13,138
that accounts
for his metamorphoses.

199
00:11:13,172 --> 00:11:18,132
The governing board of doctors
is hostile to her notion.

200
00:11:18,177 --> 00:11:20,145
They conclude
that Zelig's malady...

201
00:11:20,179 --> 00:11:23,637
can be traced to poor alignment
of the vertebrae.

202
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:26,345
Tests prove them wrong...

203
00:11:26,385 --> 00:11:29,377
and cause a temporary problem
for the patient.

204
00:11:31,057 --> 00:11:35,517
Now the press and public
hang on every bit of news...

205
00:11:35,561 --> 00:11:38,587
thoroughly absorbed
in the real-life drama.

206
00:11:38,631 --> 00:11:42,431
The continuing saga
at Manhattan Hospital goes on.

207
00:11:42,468 --> 00:11:45,631
This morning, doctors report,
experiments were conducted.

208
00:11:45,671 --> 00:11:49,004
Several women were placed
in proximity to the subject...

209
00:11:49,041 --> 00:11:50,941
but no change occurred...

210
00:11:50,976 --> 00:11:52,773
leading authorities
to conclude...

211
00:11:52,812 --> 00:11:54,643
that the phenomenon
does not occur with women.

212
00:11:54,680 --> 00:11:59,014
Doctors will experiment
with a midget and a chicken.

213
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:07,958
Leonard Zelig continues
to astound scientists...

214
00:12:07,993 --> 00:12:11,053
at New York's
Manhattan Hospital...

215
00:12:11,097 --> 00:12:13,463
where numerous tests
have led nowhere...

216
00:12:13,499 --> 00:12:16,229
in determining the nature of
this astonishing manifestation.

217
00:12:16,268 --> 00:12:19,237
He is confronted
by two overweight men...

218
00:12:19,271 --> 00:12:21,739
at the request of the doctors.

219
00:12:21,774 --> 00:12:24,242
As the men
discuss their obesity...

220
00:12:24,276 --> 00:12:26,744
an initially reticent Zelig
joins in...

221
00:12:26,779 --> 00:12:30,146
swelling himself
to a miraculous 250 pounds.

222
00:12:30,182 --> 00:12:33,379
Next, in the presence
of two Negro men...

223
00:12:33,419 --> 00:12:36,650
Zelig rapidly
becomes one himself.

224
00:12:36,689 --> 00:12:39,385
What will they think of next?

225
00:12:39,425 --> 00:12:44,328
Meanwhile, Americans all over
have their own reactions.

226
00:12:44,363 --> 00:12:48,026
I wish I could be Lenny Zelig,
the changing man.

227
00:12:48,067 --> 00:12:49,864
I'd be different people.

228
00:12:49,902 --> 00:12:52,166
Someday my wishes
will come true.

229
00:12:52,204 --> 00:12:56,664
Leonard Zelig is
one of the finest gentlemen...

230
00:12:56,709 --> 00:12:59,177
in the United States of America.

231
00:12:59,211 --> 00:13:02,738
He is the cat's pajamas.

232
00:13:02,782 --> 00:13:04,682
Trying a new approach...

233
00:13:04,717 --> 00:13:07,777
Dr. Fletcher places the subject
under hypnosis.

234
00:13:07,820 --> 00:13:12,018
Tell me why you assume
the characteristics...

235
00:13:12,057 --> 00:13:14,025
of the person you're with.

236
00:13:14,059 --> 00:13:19,622
- It's safe.
- What do you mean safe?

237
00:13:19,665 --> 00:13:22,634
Safe...

238
00:13:22,668 --> 00:13:26,126
to be like the others.

239
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:30,131
You want to be safe?

240
00:13:30,176 --> 00:13:33,145
I want to be liked.

241
00:13:34,780 --> 00:13:36,247
Probing Zelig's unconscious...

242
00:13:36,282 --> 00:13:39,251
Dr. Fletcher gradually
puts together the pieces...

243
00:13:39,285 --> 00:13:42,413
of Zelig's behavioral puzzle.

244
00:13:42,454 --> 00:13:44,922
Dividing her time
between the hospital...

245
00:13:44,957 --> 00:13:49,053
and the 42nd-Street Library,
she writes her report.

246
00:13:49,094 --> 00:13:51,562
A closed meeting
of doctors listens...

